docs.abstract: When it came time to crack down on Mac’s Public House, the Staten Island bar that has notoriously defied Covid-19 restrictions, New York City sent in law enforcement officers from the Sheriff’s Office, a relatively tiny force that relies on 150 deputies and remains unknown even to most New Yorkers.

docs.abstract: Black artists didn’t wait around for institutional change. They are making it happen.
docs.snippet: Black artists didn’t wait around for institutional change. They are making it happen.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Dear White American Theater.” So opened the scathing statement released on June 8 and signed by some of our most influential playwrights and directors who are Black, Indigenous and people of color. “We see you. We have always seen you,” the letter read a few lines later. “We have watched you pretend not to see us.”

headline.main: When Culture Really Began to Reckon With White Privilege
headline.print_headline: The Year That … Black Artists Sought Changes

docs.abstract: As the pandemic ravaged small businesses across America, some were surprised — and conflicted — about their success.
docs.snippet: As the pandemic ravaged small businesses across America, some were surprised — and conflicted — about their success.
docs.lead_paragraph: Small businesses were devastated in 2020. They have pivoted so frequently to deal with state-mandated shutdowns, new customer needs and pandemic safety protocols that many aren’t sure what direction they’re facing anymore. Nine months into the coronavirus crisis, more than a quarter remain closed, at least temporarily, according to data from Opportunity Insights, a research group at Harvard University.

headline.main: These Businesses Thrived as Others Struggled to Survive
headline.print_headline: Thriving  In a Pandemic, But Feeling  Survivor’s Guilt

docs.abstract: This was a year of protests and pivots. Monuments fell, museums looked inward. On the bright side, galleries persisted despite the pandemic’s grip and curators rolled out magisterial retrospectives.
docs.snippet: This was a year of protests and pivots. Monuments fell, museums looked inward. On the bright side, galleries persisted despite the pandemic’s grip and curators rolled out magisterial retrospectives.
docs.lead_paragraph: The year was a 12-month stress test. When I asked friends “how are you?” the repeat answers came: “anxious,” “depressed,” “bored.” The first two I could relate to, but bored is something I rarely am. As a journalist, I’m addicted to art-specific information, to taking it in, parsing it, sorting it, trying to make sense of it. And there’s been a ton of it this year, all pretty intense. So as long as I’ve had a laptop, a home library, and at least some access to “live” art, I’ve been OK in lockdown mode. Here are some things that have kept me focused.

headline.main: The Most Important Moments in Art in 2020

docs.snippet: A tough year turned out to be good for rescue animals, rotten bananas and more.
docs.lead_paragraph: We may think of 2020 as a year of seemingly endless bad news as the pandemic threatened our health, forced us to stay at home and upended most facets of life. But it wasn’t all bad. Here’s a look at some of the things that managed to come out on top.

headline.main: In 2020, These Things Came Out on Top

docs.abstract: The vaccine debate is the latest example of how our coronavirus choices are inescapably political.
docs.snippet: The vaccine debate is the latest example of how our coronavirus choices are inescapably political.
docs.lead_paragraph: One of many regrettable features of the Trump era is the way that the president’s lies and conspiracy theories have seemed to vindicate some of his opponents’ most fatuous slogans. I have in mind, in particular, the claim that has echoed through the liberal side of coronavirus-era debates — that the key to sound leadership in a pandemic is just to follow the science, to trust science and scientists, to do what experts suggest instead of letting mere grubby politics determine your response.

headline.main: When You Can’t Just ‘Trust the Science’
headline.print_headline: When You Can’t Just ‘Trust the Science’

docs.abstract: Orders to halt evictions in New York expire soon. What happens next?
docs.snippet: Orders to halt evictions in New York expire soon. What happens next?
docs.lead_paragraph: Housing activists in New York have spent much of the year preparing for the end of it. Tenant evictions have been halted or delayed by coronavirus relief measures, for the most part, until January 2021.

headline.main: The Evictions Are Coming. Housing Activists Are Ready.
